 Websockets are very useful to have when you want real time communication like messaging app or an online game server. There are different types of websockets, TCP, UDP and UNIX. In this tutorial, we will go through a basic TCP websockets, both Client and Server. Currently, it&rsquo;s only code. Explaination will be added soon.> Currently, it&rsquo;s only code. Explaination will be added soon. # TCP server> TCP server # First, let&rsquo;s start with building a TCP websocket server. Create a file name server.go. Then, add the following code.
package main import ( &#34;os&#34; ) func main() { arguments := os.Args if len(arguments) == 1 { fmt.Println(&#34;Please provide a port number
&#34;) } PORT := &#34;:&#34; + arguments[1] listener, err := net.Listen(&#34;tcp&#34;, PORT) if err != nil { fmt.Println(err) return } defer listener.Close() } I&rsquo;m using command-line arguement for PORT number. But you can declare and assign a value in the code if you want. When you run the go file, you use the command go run main.go. main.go is the first arguement with index 0. Just include the port number at the end like this: go run main.go 1234.
This code is listener, err := net.Listen(&quot;tcp&quot;, PORT) is responsible for declaring a listener. The listener waits for incoming connections from clients. It is part of net package from standard library. The Listen func accept two parameters, protocol and port number.
In the example, I used &ldquo;tcp&rdquo;. There are other options like &ldquo;udp&rdquo; and &ldquo;unix&rdquo;.
Accepting incoming TCP connections> Accepting incoming TCP connections # To establish the communication, the listener needs to accept the incoming connection. The listener.Accept() returns net.Conn which represents a connection and an error. The conn object can then be used for reading and writing data.
conn, err := listener.Accept() if err != nil { fmt.Println(err) return } Reading incoming texts> Reading incoming texts # netData, err := bufio.NewReader(conn).ReadString(&#39;
&#39;) if err != nil { fmt.Println(err) return } text := strings.TrimSpace(netData) if text == &#34;STOP&#34; { break } fmt.Println(&#34;client: &#34; + text) Responding with an integer> Responding with an integer # response := &#34;hello from server
&#34; conn.Write([]byte(string(response))) Building a TCP Client> Building a TCP Client # func main() { arguments := os.Args if len(arguments) == 1 { fmt.Println(&#34;Please provide host:port.&#34;) return } connect := arguments[1] } Establishing connection with the server> Establishing connection with the server # tcpAddr, err := net.ResolveTCPAddr(&#34;tcp4&#34;, connect) if err != nil { fmt.Println(err) return } conn, err := net.DialTCP(&#34;tcp4&#34;, nil, tcpAddr) Sending and Recieving texts> Sending and Recieving texts # for { reader := bufio.NewReader(os.Stdin) fmt.Print(&#34;&gt;&gt; &#34;) text, _ := reader.ReadString(&#39;
&#39;) fmt.Fprintf(conn, text+&#34;
